1329.definition: (of food) Not cooked, dried, frozen, or spoiled.
1329.example: After taking a beating in the boxing ring, the left side of his face looked like fresh meat.
After a day at sea it was good to feel the fresh water of the stream.

1329.definition: In a raw or untried state; uncultured; unpracticed.
1329.example: a fresh hand on a ship

1329.definition: Rude, cheeky, or inappropriate; presumptuous; disrespectful; forward.
1329.example: No one liked his fresh comments.

1329.definition: Sexually aggressive or forward; prone to caress too eagerly; overly flirtatious.
1329.example: Hey, don't get fresh with me!

1331.definition: A person other than a family member, spouse or lover whose company one enjoys and towards whom one feels affection.
1331.example: John and I have been friends ever since we were roommates at college.   Trust is important between friends.   I used to find it hard to make friends when I was shy.
The Automobile Association is every motorist's friend.   The police is every law-abiding citizen's friend.

1331.definition: A person with whom one is vaguely or indirectly acquainted.
1331.example: a friend of a friend;  I added him as a friend on Facebook, but I hardly know him.

1331.definition: A person who backs or supports something.
1331.example: I’m not a friend of cheap wine.

1331.definition: An object or idea that can be used for good.
(used only in the vocative) Used as a form of address when warning someone.
A relative, a relation by blood or marriage.
1331.example: Friends agree best at a distance.

1332.definition: Generally warm, approachable and easy to relate with in character.
Having an easy or accepting relationship with something.
Promoting the good of any person; favourable; propitious.
Of or pertaining to friendlies (friendly noun sense 2, below). Also applied to other bipolar confrontations, such as team sports
1332.example: The soldier was killed by friendly fire.

1332.definition: Being or relating to two or more natural numbers with a common abundancy.
(in compounds) Compatible with, or not damaging to (the compounded noun).
1332.example: Organic farms only use soil-friendly fertilisers.

1335.definition: Used to indicate source or provenance.
1335.example: I got a letter from my brother.

1335.definition: Used to indicate a starting point or initial reference.

1335.example: After twenty minutes, remove the cake from the oven.
A parasol protects from the sun.

1335.definition: Produced with or out of (a substance or material).
Used to indicate causation; because of, as a result of.
1335.example: Too many people die from breast cancer.

1336.definition: Located at or near the front.
1336.example: The front runner was thirty meters ahead of her nearest competitor.

1336.definition: Pronounced with the highest part of the body of the tongue toward the front of the mouth, near the hard palate (most often describing a vowel).
1336.example: The English word dress has a front vowel in most dialects.

1337.definition: A person or institution acting as the public face of some other, covert group.
1337.example: Officially it's a dry-cleaning shop, but everyone knows it's a front for the mafia.

1337.definition: An act, show, façade, persona: an intentional and false impression of oneself.
1337.example: He says he likes hip-hop, but I think it's just a front.

1338.definition: An end result, effect, or consequence; advantageous or disadvantageous result.
1338.example: His long nights in the office eventually bore fruit when his business boomed and he was given a raise.

1338.definition: Of, belonging to, related to, or having fruit or its characteristics; (of living things) producing or consuming fruit.
1338.example: the fresh-squeezed fruit juice; a fruit salad; an artificial fruit flavor; a fruit tree; a fruit bat
Blessed art thou amongst women and blessed is the fruit of thy womb.

1340.definition: Something that stimulates, encourages or maintains an action.
1340.example: His books were fuel for the revolution.

1341.definition: To satisfy, carry out, bring to completion (an obligation, a requirement, etc.).
1341.example: You made a promise, son, and now you must fulfill it.

1341.definition: To emotionally or artistically satisfy; to develop one's gifts to the fullest.
1341.example: This is the most fulfilling work I've ever done.

1341.definition: To obey, follow, comply with (a rule, requirement etc.).
1341.example: Unfortunately, you don't fulfill the criteria for extra grants at the present time.

1341.definition: To fill full; fill to the utmost capacity; fill up.
1341.example: My lady is positively fulfilled of grace.

1342.definition: Containing the maximum possible amount that can fit in the space available.
1342.example: The jugs were full to the point of overflowing.
Our book gives full treatment to the subject of angling.
She had tattoos the full length of her arms.   He was prosecuted to the full extent of the law.

1342.definition: Having eaten to satisfaction, having a "full" stomach; replete.
1342.example: "I'm full," he said, pushing back from the table.
I prefer my pizzas full of toppings.
full lips; a full face; a full figure

1342.definition: Of a garment, of a size that is ample, wide, or having ample folds or pleats to be comfortable.
1342.example: a full pleated skirt;   She needed her full clothing during her pregnancy.

1342.definition: Having the attention, thoughts, etc., absorbed in any matter, and the feelings more or less excited by it.
1342.example: She's full of her latest project.

1342.definition: (postnominal) Said of the three cards of the same rank in a full house.
1342.example: I'll beat him with my kings full! = three kings and two unspecified cards of the same rank.

1343.definition: In a full manner; without lack or defect.
In a full degree; to a full extent.
1343.example: He is fully capable of meeting his responsibilities.

1344.example: He is such a fun person to be with.
This year's fashion style is much more fun than recent seasons.

1347.definition: A sum or source of money.
1347.example: a fund for the maintenance of underprivileged students

1347.definition: A money-management operation, such as a mutual fund.
1347.example: Several major funds were declared insolvent recently.

1347.definition: A large supply of something to be drawn upon.
1347.example: He drew on his immense fund of knowledge.

1348.example: He used his inheritance to fund his gambling addiction.

1349.definition: Essential, as an element, principle, or law; important; original; elementary.
1349.example: A need for belonging seems fundamental to humans.

1350.definition: A ceremony to honour and remember a deceased person. Often distinguished from a memorial service by the presence of the body of the deceased.
1350.example: Many mourners turned up at the local artist's funeral to pay homage.

1351.example: When I went to the circus, I only found the clowns funny.

1351.definition: Strange or unusual, often implying unpleasant.
1351.example: I've got a funny feeling that this isn't going to work.

1352.definition: Large movable item(s), usually in a room, which enhance(s) the room's characteristics, functionally or decoratively.
1352.example: A chair is furniture. Sofas are also furniture.

1353.definition: (comparative form of far) To, at or over a greater distance in space, time or other extent.
1353.example: I can run further than you.

1353.definition: (comparative form of far) To a greater extent or degree.
1353.example: Of the two civilisations, this one was further advanced.

1353.definition: Beyond what is already stated or is already the case.
1353.example: Chapter 10 further explains the ideas introduced in Chapter 9.
It is overlong, and further, it makes no sense.
Further to our recent telephone call, I am writing to clarify certain points raised.

1354.definition: Excessive activity, worry, bother, or talk about something.
1354.example: They made a big fuss about the wedding plans.

1354.definition: A complaint or noise; a scene.
1354.example: If you make enough of a fuss about the problem, maybe they'll fix it for you.

1354.definition: An exhibition of affection or admiration.
1354.example: They made a great fuss over the new baby.

1355.definition: Having to do with or occurring in the future.
1355.example: Future generations will either laugh or cry at our stupidity.

1356.definition: Goodness in what is yet to come. Something to look forward to.
1356.example: There is no future in dwelling on the past.

1358.example: Looks like you've gained a new friend.

1358.definition: To have or receive advantage or profit; to acquire gain; to grow rich; to advance in interest, health, or happiness; to make progress.
To come off winner or victor in; to be successful in; to obtain by competition.
1358.example: to gain a battle; to gain a case at law

1358.definition: To be more likely to catch or overtake an individual.

1358.example: to gain the top of a mountain

1359.definition: A browsable collection of images, font styles, etc.
1359.example: a clip-art gallery in a wordprocessor

1360.definition: (nearly always singular) A field of gainful activity, as an industry or profession.
1360.example: He's in the securities game somehow.

1360.definition: Something that resembles a game with rules, despite not being designed.
1360.example: In the game of life, you may find yourself playing the waiting game far too often.
The forest has plenty of game.

1360.definition: (used mostly of males) The ability to seduce someone, usually by strategy.
1360.example: He didn't get anywhere with her because he had no game.

1360.definition: A questionable or unethical practice in pursuit of a goal; a scheme.
1360.example: You want to borrow my credit card for a week? What's your game?

1361.definition: A number going in company; a number of friends or persons associated for a particular purpose.
1361.example: The gang from our office is going out for drinks Friday night.

1361.definition: A group of laborers under one foreman; a squad.
1361.example: a gang of sailors; a railroad gang

1361.definition: A criminal group with a common cultural background and identifying features, often associated with a particular section of a city.
1361.example: a youth gang; a neighborhood gang; motorcycle gang.

1361.definition: A group of criminals or alleged criminals who band together for mutual protection and profit.
1361.example: The Winter Hill Gang was quite proficient at murdering rival mobsters in order to take over their rackets.

1361.definition: A group of politicians united in furtherance of a political goal.
1361.example: Not all members of the Gang of Six are consistent in their opposition to filibuster.

1361.definition: A combination of similar tools or implements arranged so as, by acting together, to save time or labor; a set.
1361.example: a gang of saws; a gang of plows.

1361.definition: A set; all required for an outfit.
(electrics) A number of switches or other electrical devices wired into one unit and covered by one faceplate.
1361.example: an outlet gang box; a double gang switch.

1361.definition: (electrics) A group of wires attached as a bundle.
1361.example: Do a drop for the telephone gang, then another drop for the Internet gang, both through the ceiling of the wiring closet.

1362.definition: An opening in anything made by breaking or parting.
1362.example: He made a gap in the fence by kicking at a weak spot.

1362.definition: An opening allowing passage or entrance.
1362.example: We can slip through that gap between the buildings.

1362.definition: An opening that implies a breach or defect.
1362.example: There is a gap between the roof and the gutter.
I have a gap in my schedule next Tuesday.

1362.definition: A hiatus, a pause in something which is otherwise continuous.
A vacancy, deficit, absence, or lack.
1362.example: Find words to fill the gaps in an incomplete sentence.
The exploring party went through the high gap in the mountains.

1362.definition: A sheltered area of coast between two cliffs (mostly restricted to place names).
1362.example: At Birling Gap we can stop and go have a picnic on the beach.

1364.definition: Food waste material of any kind.
1364.example: Garbage is collected on Tuesdays; rubbish on Fridays

1364.definition: Useless or disposable material; waste material of any kind.
1364.example: The garbage truck collects all residential municipal waste.

1364.definition: A place or receptacle for waste material.
1364.example: He threw the newspaper into the garbage.

1365.definition: An outdoor area containing one or more types of plants, usually plants grown for food or ornamental purposes.
1365.example: a vegetable garden  a flower garden

1365.definition: The grounds at the front or back of a house.
1365.example: This house has a swimming pool, a tent, a swing set and a fountain in the garden.  We were drinking lemonade and playing croquet in the garden.  Our garden is overgrown with weeds.

1365.definition: Pubic hair or the genitalia it masks.
1365.example: N.B. From a commentary on Song of Solomon 4:16, which was written in Hebrew c. 950 BC; book footnotes are shown here within brackets. Many scholars disagree with this Biblical interpretation, which is included as evidence of the word's usage in 1995 rather than its intended meaning in 950 BC.

1367.definition: Matter in a state intermediate between liquid and plasma that can be contained only if it is fully surrounded by a solid (or in a bubble of liquid) (or held together by gravitational pull); it can condense into a liquid, or can (rarely) become a solid directly.
1367.example: A lot of gas had escaped from the cylinder.

1367.definition: A chemical element or compound in such a state.
1367.example: The atmosphere is made up of a number of different gases.

1367.definition: A flammable gaseous hydrocarbon or hydrocarbon mixture (typically predominantly methane) used as a fuel, e.g. for cooking, heating, electricity generation or as a fuel in internal combustion engines in vehicles.
1367.example: Gas-fired power stations have largely replaced coal-burning ones.

1367.definition: A hob on a gas cooker.
1367.example: She turned the gas on, put the potatoes on, then lit the oven.

1367.definition: Methane or other waste gases trapped in one's belly as a result of the digestive process.
1367.example: My tummy hurts so bad, I have gas.

1367.definition: A humorous or entertaining event or person.

1367.example: The closer threw him nothing but gas.

1368.example: The refinery produces a wide range of gasolines.

1369.example: The gate in front of the railroad crossing went up after the train had passed.

1369.definition: The gap between a batsman's bat and pad.
1369.example: Singh was bowled through the gate, a very disappointing way for a world-class batsman to get out.

1370.example: I've been gathering ideas from the people I work with.

1370.definition: To bring parts of a whole closer.
1370.example: She gathered the shawl about her as she stepped into the cold.

1370.definition: To infer or conclude; to know from a different source.
1370.example: From his silence, I gathered that things had not gone well.

1370.definition: (of a boil or sore) To be filled with pus
1370.example: Salt water can help boils to gather and then burst.

1371.example: Pennsylvania Dutch include the plain folk and the gay folk.

1373.definition: A segment of DNA or RNA from a cell's or an organism's genome, that may take several forms and thus parameterizes a phenomenon, in general the structure of a protein; locus.
1373.example: A change in a gene is reflected in the protein or RNA molecule that it codes for.

1375.example: It is generally known that the Earth is round.
I generally have a walk in the afternoon.

1376.definition: To bring into being; give rise to.
To produce as a result of a chemical or physical process.
1376.example: Adding concentrated sulphuric acid to water generates heat.

1376.definition: To form a figure from a curve or solid.
1376.example: Rotating a circle generates a sphere.

1377.definition: A single step or stage in the succession of natural descent; a rank or degree in genealogy, the members of a family from the same parents, considered as a single unit.
1377.example: This is the book of the generations of Adam - Genesis 5:1

1377.definition: The formation or production of any geometrical magnitude, as a line, a surface, a solid, by the motion, in accordance with a mathematical law, of a point or a magnitude, by the motion of a point, of a surface by a line, a sphere by a semicircle, etc.
1377.example: the generation of a line or curve

1377.definition: A specific age range whose members can relate culturally to one another.
1377.example: Generation X grew up in the eighties, whereas the generation known as the millennials grew up in the nineties.

1377.definition: A version of a form of pop culture which differs from later or earlier versions.
1377.example: People sometimes dispute which generation of Star Trek is best, including the original and The Next Generation.

1378.definition: Noble in behaviour or actions; principled, not petty; kind, magnanimous.
1378.example: Thank you for your generous words.

1378.definition: Willing to give and share unsparingly; showing a readiness to give more (especially money) than is expected or needed.
1378.example: She's been extremely generous with her winnings.
Add a generous helping of mayonnaise.

1379.definition: Tender and amiable; of a considerate or kindly disposition.
1379.example: Stuart is a gentle man; he would never hurt you.

1379.definition: Soft and mild rather than hard or severe.
1379.example: I felt something touch my shoulder; it was gentle and a little slimy.
We had a gentle swim in the lake.

1379.definition: Gradual rather than steep or sudden.
1379.example: The walks in this area have a gentle incline.

1379.definition: Polite and respectful rather than rude.
1379.example: He gave me a gentle reminder that we had to hurry up.

1380.definition: A man of gentle but not noble birth, particularly a man of means (originally ownership of property) who does not work for a living but has no official status in a peerage; an armiferous man ranking below a knight.
1380.example: Being a gentleman, Robert was entitled to shove other commoners into the gongpit but he still had to jump out of the way of the knights to avoid the same fate himself.
Well, la-di-da, aren't you just a proper gentleman?
Please escort this gentleman to the gentlemen's room.

1382.definition: Not counterfeit, spurious, false, or adulterated
1382.example: a genuine text;  a genuine production;  genuine materials; genuine friendship

1383.definition: (ditransitive) To obtain; to acquire.
1383.example: I'm going to get a computer tomorrow from the discount store.

1383.definition: To receive.
1383.example: He got a severe reprimand for that.

1383.definition: (in a perfect construction, with present-tense meaning) To have. See usage notes.
1383.example: I've got a concert ticket for you.

1383.definition: To fetch, bring, take.
1383.example: Can you get my bag from the living-room, please?

1383.definition: To become, or cause oneself to become.
1383.example: I'm getting hungry; how about you?

1383.definition: To cause to become; to bring about.
1383.example: I can't get these boots off (or on).

1383.definition: To cause to do.
1383.example: I can't get it to work.

1383.definition: To cause to come or go or move.
1383.example: I got him to his room.

1383.definition: To cause to be in a certain status or position.
1383.example: Get him here at once.

1383.definition: (with various prepositions, such as into, over, or behind; for specific idiomatic senses see individual entries get into, get over, etc.) To adopt, assume, arrive at, or progress towards (a certain position, location, state).
1383.example: I'm getting into a muddle.

1383.definition: To cover (a certain distance) while travelling.
1383.example: to get a mile

1383.definition: To begin (doing something or to do something).
1383.example: After lunch we got chatting.

1383.definition: To take or catch (a scheduled transportation service).
1383.example: I normally get the 7:45 train.

1383.definition: To respond to (a telephone call, a doorbell, etc).
1383.example: Can you get that call, please? I'm busy.

1383.definition: (followed by infinitive) To be able, be permitted, or have the opportunity (to do something desirable or ironically implied to be desirable).
1383.example: Great. I get to clean the toilets today.

1383.definition: To understand. (compare get it)
1383.example: I don't get what you mean by "fun". This place sucks!

1383.definition: To be told; be the recipient of (a question, comparison, opinion, etc.).
1383.example: "You look just like Helen Mirren." / "I get that a lot."

1383.definition: To be. Used to form the passive of verbs.
1383.example: He got bitten by a dog.

1383.definition: To become ill with or catch (a disease).
1383.example: I went on holiday and got malaria.

1383.definition: To catch out, trick successfully.
1383.example: He keeps calling pretending to be my boss—it gets me every time.

1383.definition: To perplex, stump.
1383.example: That question's really got me.

1383.definition: To find as an answer.
1383.example: What did you get for question four?

1383.definition: To bring to reckoning; to catch (as a criminal); to effect retribution.
1383.example: I'm gonna get him for that.

1383.definition: To hear completely; catch.
1383.example: Sorry, I didn't get that. Could you repeat it?

1383.definition: To getter.
1383.example: I put the getter into the container to get the gases.

1383.definition: To learn; to commit to memory; to memorize; sometimes with out.
1383.example: to get a lesson;  to get out one's Greek lesson

1383.definition: Used with a personal pronoun to indicate that someone is being pretentious or grandiose.
1383.example: Get her with her new hairdo.

1383.definition: To kill.
1383.example: They’re coming to get you, Barbara.

1383.definition: To measure.
1383.example: Did you get her temperature?

1385.example: She had a gift for playing the flute.

1385.definition: The act, right, or power of giving or bestowing.
1385.example: The office is in the gift of the President.

1386.example: Your girl turned up on our doorstep.

1386.definition: A boy or man who is weak or sentimental.

1387.definition: A female partner in an unmarried romantic relationship.
1387.example: Marc went to the park with his girlfriend and watched the sunset with her.
Mary always enjoyed hanging out with her girlfriend Jessica.

1388.definition: (ditransitive) To estimate or predict (a duration or probability) for (something).
1388.example: I give it a 95% chance of success.

1388.definition: To collapse under pressure or force.
1388.example: One pillar gave, then more, and suddenly the whole floor pancaked onto the floor below.

1388.definition: To provide, as, a service or a broadcast.

1388.example: The master bedroom gives onto a spacious balcony.

1388.definition: To exhibit as a product or result; to produce; to yield.
1388.example: The number of men, divided by the number of ships, gives four hundred to each ship.

1388.definition: To allow or admit by way of supposition; to concede.
1388.example: He can be bad-tempered, I'll give you that, but he's a hard worker.

1388.definition: To communicate or announce (advice, tidings, etc.); to pronounce or utter (an opinion, a judgment, a shout, etc.).
1388.example: The umpire finally gave his decision: the ball was out.
That boy is given to fits of bad temper.

1388.definition: To be going on, to be occurring

1389.example: I'm glad the rain has finally stopped.

1390.definition: Any of various sulphides, mostly dark-coloured, which have a brilliant metallic lustre.

1391.definition: An amorphous solid, often transparent substance made by melting sand with a mixture of soda, potash and lime.
1391.example: A popular myth is that window glass is actually an extremely viscous liquid.

1391.definition: A vessel from which one drinks, especially one made of glass, plastic, or similar translucent or semi-translucent material.
1391.example: Fill my glass with milk, please.

1391.definition: (metonymically) The quantity of liquid contained in such a vessel.
1391.example: There is half a glass of milk in each pound of chocolate we produce.
She adjusted her lipstick in the glass.

1391.definition: (in names of species) Transparent or translucent.
1391.example: glass frog;  glass shrimp;  glass worm
Her new camera was incompatible with her old one, so she needed to buy new glass.

1392.definition: Concerning all parts of the world.

1392.example: In the center was a small, global mass.

1393.definition: An item of clothing other than a mitten, covering all or part of the hand and fingers, but usually allowing independent movement of the fingers.
1393.example: I wore gloves to keep my hands warm.

1393.definition: The ability to catch a hit ball.
1393.example: Frederico had a great glove, but he couldn't hit a curveball, so he never broke into the pros.

1393.definition: (with definite article) A challenge from one to another.
1393.example: to throw down the glove, i.e. to offer a challenge; to take up the glove, to accept it

1394.definition: A turn at something, or in something (e.g. a game).
An approval or permission to do something, or that which has been approved.
1394.example: We will begin as soon as the boss says it's a go.

1394.definition: Power of going or doing; energy; vitality; perseverance.
1394.example: There is no go in him.
ate it all in one go

1395.definition: (chiefly of a machine) To work or function (properly); to move or perform (as required).
1395.example: The engine just won't go anymore.

1395.definition: To start; to begin (an action or process).
1395.example: Get ready, get set, go!

1395.definition: To take a turn, especially in a game.
1395.example: It’s your turn; go.

1395.definition: To attend.
1395.example: I go to school at the schoolhouse.

1395.definition: To extend (from one point in time or space to another).
1395.example: This property goes all the way to the state line.

1395.definition: To lead (to a place); to give access to.
1395.example: Does this road go to Fort Smith?

1395.definition: To become. (The adjective that follows usually describes a negative state.)
1395.example: After failing as a criminal, he decided to go straight.

1395.definition: To continuously or habitually be in a state.
1395.example: I don't want my children to go hungry.

1395.definition: To come to (a certain condition or state).
1395.example: They went into debt, she goes to sleep around 10 o'clock.

1395.definition: To change (from one value to another) in the meaning of wend.
1395.example: The traffic light went straight from green to red.

1395.definition: To turn out, to result; to come to (a certain result).
1395.example: How did your meeting with Smith go?

1395.definition: To tend (toward a result).
1395.example: These experiences go to make us stronger.

1395.definition: To contribute to a (specified) end product or result.
1395.example: qualities that go to make a lady / lip-reader / sharpshooter

1395.definition: To be discarded.
1395.example: This chair has got to go.

1395.definition: To be sold.
1395.example: Everything must go.

1395.definition: To be given, especially to be assigned or allotted.
1395.example: The award went to Steven Spielberg.

1395.definition: To survive or get by; to last or persist for a stated length of time.
1395.example: Can you two go twenty minutes without arguing?!

1395.definition: To have a certain record.
1395.example: The team is going five in a row.

1395.definition: To be expressed or composed (a certain way).
1395.example: As the story goes, he got the idea for the song while sitting in traffic.

1395.definition: To resort (to).
1395.example: I'll go to court if I have to.

1395.definition: To date.
1395.example: He's been going with her for two weeks.

1395.definition: To be in general; to be usually.
1395.example: As sentences go, this one is pretty boring.

1395.definition: To take (a particular part or share); to participate in to the extent of.
1395.example: Let's go halves on this.

1395.definition: To yield or weigh.
1395.example: Those babies go five tons apiece.

1395.definition: To offer, bid or bet an amount; to pay.
1395.example: I'll go a ten-spot.

1395.definition: To enjoy. (Compare go for.)
1395.example: I could go a beer right about now.

1395.definition: To urinate or defecate.
1395.example: Have you managed to go today, Mrs. Miggins?

1396.definition: A result that one is attempting to achieve.
1396.example: My lifelong goal is to get into a Hollywood movie.

1397.definition: A deity or supreme being; a supernatural, typically immortal, being with superior powers, to which personhood is attributed.
1397.example: The most frequently used name for the Islamic god is Allah.
Lounging on the beach were several Greek gods.

1399.example: France has won three golds and five silvers.

1400.definition: Made of, or relating to, gold.
Having a colour or other richness suggestive of gold.

1400.example: The Renaissance was a golden era.
It's not long until our golden wedding.

1400.definition: Relating to the elderly or retired.
1400.example: After retiring, Bob and Judy moved to Arizona to live out their golden years.

1402.definition: (when with and) Very, extremely. See good and.
1402.example: The soup is good and hot.

1403.definition: Used as a greeting when meeting somebody for the first time in the morning.

1480.definition: (auxiliary verb, taking a to-infinitive) See have to.
1480.example: I have to go.

1480.definition: To give birth to.
1480.example: My mother had me when she was 25.

1480.definition: To engage in sexual intercourse with.
1480.example: He's always bragging about how many women he's had.

1480.definition: To accept as a romantic partner.
1480.example: Despite my protestations of love, she would not have me.

1480.definition: (transitive with bare infinitive) To cause to, by a command, request or invitation.
1480.example: They had me feed their dog while they were out of town.

1480.definition: (transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement) To cause to be.
1480.example: He had him arrested for trespassing.

1480.definition: (transitive with bare infinitive) To be affected by an occurrence. (Used in supplying a topic that is not a verb argument.)
1480.example: I've had three people today tell me my hair looks nice.

1480.definition: (transitive with adjective or adjective-phrase complement) To depict as being.
1480.example: Their stories differed; he said he'd been at work when the incident occurred, but her statement had him at home that entire evening.

1480.definition: To defeat in a fight; take.
1480.example: I could have him!

1480.definition: (obsolete outside Ireland) To be able to speak (a language).
1480.example: I have no German.

1480.definition: To feel or be (especially painfully) aware of.
1480.example: Dan certainly has arms today, probably from scraping paint off four columns the day before.

1480.definition: To trick, to deceive.
1480.example: You had me alright! I never would have thought that was just a joke.

1480.definition: (often with present participle) To allow; to tolerate.
1480.example: I asked my dad if I could go to the concert this Thursday, but he wouldn't have it since it's a school night.

1480.definition: (often used in the negative) To believe, buy, be taken in by.
1480.example: I made up an excuse as to why I was out so late, but my wife wasn't having any of it.

1480.definition: To host someone; to take in as a guest.
1480.example: Thank you for having me!

1480.definition: To get a reading, measurement, or result from an instrument or calculation.
1480.example: I have two contacts on my scope.

1480.definition: (of a jury) To consider a court proceeding that has been completed; to begin deliberations on a case.
1480.example: We'll schedule closing arguments for Thursday, and the jury will have the case by that afternoon.

1481.example: Is your cat a he or a she?

1481.definition: (personal, sometimes proscribed, see usage notes) A person whose gender is unknown or irrelevant.
1481.example: The rulebook clearly states that "if any student is caught cheating, he will be expelled", and you were caught cheating, were you not, Anna?

1482.definition: The part of the body of an animal or human which contains the brain, mouth and main sense organs.
1482.example: Be careful when you pet that dog on the head; it may bite.

1482.definition: The topmost, foremost, or leading part.
1482.example: What does it say at the head of the page?
We are having a difficult time making head against this wind.
We will consider performance issues under the head of future improvements.
These isses are going to come to a head today.

1483.definition: To be in command of. (See also head up.)
1483.example: Who heads the board of trustees?

1483.definition: To come at the beginning of; to commence.
1483.example: A group of clowns headed the procession.

1483.definition: To move in a specified direction.
To remove the head from a fish.
1483.example: The salmon are first headed and then scaled.
This kind of cabbage heads early.

1483.definition: To form a head to; to fit or furnish with a head.
To cut off the top of; to lop off.

1483.example: to head a drove of cattle

1483.definition: To get in the front of, so as to hinder or stop; to oppose.
1483.example: The wind headed the ship and made progress difficult.

1485.definition: The state of being free from physical or psychological disease, illness, or malfunction; wellness.
1485.example: Her mental health is really affected by stressful environments.

1485.definition: A state of well-being or balance, often physical but sometimes also mental and social; the overall level of function of an organism from the cellular (micro) level to the social (macro) level.
1485.example: The directors are concerned about the financial health of the project.

1485.definition: The amount of damage an in-game object can withstand before it is destroyed.
1485.example: The enemies on this level have a lot of health.

1486.definition: Enjoying health and vigor of body, mind, or spirit: well.
1486.example: He was father to three healthy kids.
A healthy diet and exercise can help to maintain proper weight.
Sam unwrapped the sandwich and took a healthy bite out of the middle.

1487.definition: (stative) To perceive sounds through the ear.
1487.example: I was deaf, and now I can hear.

1487.definition: (stative) To perceive (a sound, or something producing a sound) with the ear, to recognize (something) in an auditory way.
1487.example: I heard a sound from outside the window.

1487.definition: To listen favourably to; to grant (a request etc.).
1487.example: Eventually the king chose to hear her entreaties.

1487.definition: To listen to (a person, case) in a court of law; to try.
1487.example: Your case will be heard at the end of the month.

1487.definition: To sympathize with; to understand the feelings or opinion of.
1487.example: You're tired of all the ads on TV? I hear ya.

1488.definition: The sense used to perceive sound.
1488.example: My hearing isn't what it used to be, but I still heard that noise.

1488.definition: A proceeding at which discussions are heard.
1488.example: There will be a public hearing to discuss the new traffic light.

1489.definition: Emotions, kindness, moral effort, or spirit in general.
1489.example: The team lost, but they showed a lot of heart.

1489.definition: The seat of the affections or sensibilities, collectively or separately, as love, hate, joy, grief, courage, etc.; rarely, the seat of the understanding or will; usually in a good sense; personality.
1489.example: a good, tender, loving, bad, hard, or selfish heart

1489.definition: A term of affectionate or kindly and familiar address.
1489.example: Listen, dear heart, we must go now.
Buddhists believe that suffering is right at the heart of all life.

1490.example: This furnace puts out 5000 BTUs of heat.   That engine is really throwing off some heat.   Removal of heat from the liquid caused it to turn into a solid.

1490.definition: The condition or quality of being hot.
1490.example: Stay out of the heat of the sun!

1490.definition: An attribute of a spice that causes a burning sensation in the mouth.
1490.example: The chili sauce gave the dish heat.

1490.definition: A period of intensity, particularly of emotion.
1490.example: It's easy to make bad decisions in the heat of the moment.
The heat from her family after her DUI arrest was unbearable.
The catcher called for the heat, high and tight.

1490.definition: A condition where a mammal is aroused sexually or where it is especially fertile and therefore eager to mate.
1490.example: The male canines were attracted by the female in heat.

1490.definition: A preliminary race, used to determine the participants in a final race
1490.example: The runner had high hopes, but was out of contention after the first heat.

1490.definition: One cycle of bringing metal to maximum temperature and working it until it is too cool to work further.
1490.example: I can make a scroll like that in a single heat.
The children stayed indoors during this year's summer heat.

1490.definition: Heating system; a system that raises the temperature of a room or building.
1490.example: I'm freezing; could you turn on the heat?

1490.definition: The output of a heating system.
1490.example: During the power outage we had no heat because the controls are electric.   Older folks like more heat than the young.

1491.definition: To cause an increase in temperature of (an object or space); to cause to become hot (often with "up").

1491.example: There's a pot of soup heating on the stove.

1492.definition: A device that produces and radiates heat, typically to raise the temperature of a room or building.
1492.example: Turn on the heater; I'm cold.
The thug pumped two rounds from his heater into her.

1492.definition: A fastball, especially one thrown at high velocity.
1492.example: Jones threw a heater under his chin.
Emmy went on a heater in Las Vegas and came back six thousand dollars richer.

1493.definition: The act of making something hot.
1493.example: The crucible was subjected to several heatings.

1495.example: He clomped heavily up the stairs in his boots.

1495.definition: To a considerable degree, to a great extent.
In a manner designed for heavy duty.
1495.example: heavily armed soldiers;   heavily armoured tanks;   heavily reinforced walls

1495.definition: So as to be thick or heavy.
1495.example: heavily built young men;   his heavily muscled arms

1496.definition: Not easy to bear; burdensome; oppressive.
1496.example: heavy yokes, expenses, undertakings, trials, news, etc.
The Moody Blues are, like, heavy.
Come heavy, or not at all.

1496.definition: (of a person) Doing the specified activity more intensely than most other people.
1496.example: He was a heavy sleeper, a heavy eater and a heavy smoker – certainly not an ideal husband.

1496.definition: (of food) High in fat or protein; difficult to digest.
1496.example: Cheese-stuffed sausage is too heavy to eat before exercising.

1496.definition: Of great force, power, or intensity; deep or intense.
1496.example: it was a heavy storm;  a heavy slumber in bed;  a heavy punch
his eyes were heavy with sleep;  she was heavy with child

1496.definition: Slow; sluggish; inactive; or lifeless, dull, inanimate, stupid.
1496.example: a heavy gait, looks, manners, style, etc.
a heavy road; a heavy soil

1497.definition: The highest point or maximum degree.
1497.example: She's at the height of her career.

1499.definition: A greeting (salutation) said when meeting someone or acknowledging someone’s arrival or presence.
A greeting used when answering the telephone.
1499.example: Hello? How may I help you?

1499.definition: A call for response if it is not clear if anyone is present or listening, or if a telephone conversation may have been disconnected.
Used sarcastically to imply that the person addressed or referred to has done something the speaker or writer considers to be foolish.
1499.example: You just tried to start your car with your cell phone. Hello?

1499.definition: An expression of puzzlement or discovery.

1501.definition: Action given to provide assistance; aid.
1501.example: I need some help with my homework.

1501.definition: (usually uncountable) Something or someone which provides assistance with a task.
1501.example: He was a great help to me when I was moving house.

1501.definition: Documentation provided with computer software, etc. and accessed using the computer.
1501.example: I can't find anything in the help about rotating an image.

1501.definition: (usually uncountable) One or more people employed to help in the maintenance of a house or the operation of a farm or enterprise.
1501.example: Most of the hired help is seasonal, for the harvest.

1501.definition: Correction of deficits, as by psychological counseling or medication or social support or remedial training.
1501.example: He really needs help in handling customer complaints.

1502.definition: To provide assistance to (someone or something).
1502.example: He helped his grandfather cook breakfast.

1502.definition: To assist (a person) in getting something, especially food or drink at table; used with to.
1502.example: Help yourself to whatever's in the fridge.

1502.definition: To contribute in some way to.
1502.example: If you want to get a job, it helps to have some prior experience.

1502.definition: To avoid; to prevent; to refrain from; to restrain (oneself). Usually used in nonassertive contexts with can.
1502.example: Are they going to beat us? Not if I can help it!

1504.definition: From here, from this place, away
From the living or from this world
1504.example: After a long battle, my poor daughter was taken hence.

1504.definition: (of a length of time) in the future from now
1504.example: A year hence it will be forgotten.

1504.definition: As a result; therefore, for this reason
1504.example: I shall go to Japan and hence will not be here in time for the party.

1506.example: I think this bird is a him, but it may be a her.

1507.definition: (location) In, on, or at this place.
(location) To this place; used in place of the more dated hither.

1507.example: Derivatives can refer to anything that is derived from something else, but here they refer specifically to functions that give the slope of the tangent line to a curve.

1507.definition: At this point in the argument, narration, or other, usually written, work.

1508.definition: The current player, especially an hypothetical player for example and didactic purposes. Compare: villain. Not to be confused with hero call.
1508.example: Let's discuss how to play if the hero has KK, and there's an ace on board.

1509.example: I think this bird is a him, but it may be a her.

1510.definition: (reflexive pronoun) Her; the female object of a verb or preposition that also appears as the subject.
She; an intensive repetition of the female subject, often used to indicate the exclusiveness of that person as the only satisfier of the predicate.
The subject or non-reflexive object of a predicate; she (used of upper-class ladies, or sarcastically, of women who imagine themselves to be more important than others)
1510.example: Have you seen herself yet this morning?

1511.definition: To stop or pause respecting decision or action; to be in suspense or uncertainty as to a determination.
1511.example: He hesitated whether to accept the offer or not; men often hesitate in forming a judgment.

1512.definition: A friendly, informal, casual greeting said when meeting someone.

1513.definition: To put (something) in a place where it will be harder to discover or out of sight.
1513.example: He hides his magazines under the bed.

1514.definition: Very elevated; extending or being far above a base; tall; lofty.
1514.example: The balloon rose high in the sky.   The wall was high.   a high mountain

1514.definition: Having a specified elevation or height; tall.
1514.example: three feet high   three Mount Everests high

1514.definition: Elevated in status, esteem, prestige; exalted in rank, station, or character.
1514.example: The oldest of the elves' royal family still conversed in High Elvish.

1514.definition: Of great importance and consequence: grave (if negative) or solemn (if positive).
1514.example: high crimes, the high festival of the sun

1514.definition: Consummate; advanced (e.g. in development) to the utmost extent or culmination, or possessing a quality in its supreme degree, at its zenith.
1514.example: high (i.e. intense) heat; high (i.e. full or quite) noon; high (i.e. rich or spicy) seasoning; high (i.e. complete) pleasure; high (i.e. deep or vivid) colour; high (i.e. extensive, thorough) scholarship; high tide; high [tourism] season; the High Middle Ages

1514.definition: (in several set phrases) Remote in distance or time.
Elevated in mood; marked by great merriment, excitement, etc.
Lofty, often to the point of arrogant, haughty, boastful, proud.
Large, great (in amount or quantity, value, force, energy, etc).
1514.example: My bank charges me a high interest rate.   I was running a high temperature and had high cholesterol.   high voltage   high prices   high winds   a high number

1514.definition: (acoustics) Acute or shrill in pitch, due to being of greater frequency, i.e. produced by more rapid vibrations (wave oscillations).
1514.example: The note was too high for her to sing.

1514.definition: (of meat, especially venison) Strong-scented; slightly tainted/spoiled; beginning to decompose.
1514.example: Epicures do not cook game before it is high.

1515.definition: In or to an elevated position.
1515.example: How high above land did you fly?

1515.definition: In or at a great value.
1515.example: Costs have grown higher this year again.

1515.definition: At a pitch of great frequency.
1515.example: I certainly can't sing that high.

1517.definition: In a high or esteemed manner.

1517.example: He is in a highly visible job.

1519.definition: An elevated location smaller than a mountain.
1519.example: The park is sheltered from the wind by a hill to the east.
You need to pick up speed to get up the hill that's coming up.

1519.definition: A single cluster or group of plants growing close together, and having the earth heaped up about them.
1519.example: a hill of corn or potatoes

1520.example: I think this bird is a him, but it may be a her.

1521.definition: (reflexive pronoun) Him; the male object of a verb or preposition that also appears as the subject
He; used as an intensifier, often to emphasize that the referent is the exclusive participant in the predicate
The subject or non-reflexive object of a predicate; he (used of upper-class gentlemen, or sarcastically, of men who imagine themselves to be more important than others)
1521.example: Has himself come down to breakfast yet?

1522.definition: To obtain the services of in return for fixed payment.
1522.example: We hired a car for two weeks because ours had broken down.

1522.definition: To employ; to obtain the services of (a person) in exchange for remuneration; to give someone a job.
1522.example: The company had problems when it tried to hire more skilled workers.

1522.definition: To exchange the services of for remuneration.
1522.example: They hired themselves out as day laborers.  They hired out their basement for Inauguration week.

1522.definition: To accomplish by paying for services.
1522.example: After waiting two years for her husband to finish the tiling, she decided to hire it done.
They hired out as day laborers.

1523.definition: That which belongs to him; the possessive case of he, used without a following noun.
1523.example: The decision was his to live with.

1523.definition: The word "hi" used as a greeting.
1523.example: I didn't even get a hi.

1525.definition: Of, concerning, or in accordance with recorded history, (particularly) as opposed to legends, myths, and fictions.
1525.example: July 4, 1776, is a historic date. A great deal of historical research has been done on the events leading up to that day.

1525.definition: Of, concerning, or in accordance with the scholarly discipline of history.
Forming compound adjectives with the meaning "historical/~" or "historically":

1526.example: History repeats itself if we don’t learn from its mistakes.

1526.definition: The branch of knowledge that studies the past; the assessment of notable events.
1526.example: He teaches history at the university.   History will not look kindly on these tyrants.   He dreams of an invention that will make history.

1526.definition: A set of events involving an entity.
1526.example: What is your medical history?   The family's history includes events best forgotten.

1526.definition: A record or narrative description of past events.
1526.example: I really enjoyed Shakespeare's tragedies more than his histories.

1526.definition: A list of past and continuing medical conditions of an individual or family.
1526.example: A personal medical history is required for the insurance policy.   He has a history of cancer in his family.

1526.definition: A record of previous user events, especially of visited web pages in a browser.
1526.example: I visited a great site yesterday but forgot the URL. Luckily, I didn't clear my history.

1526.definition: Something that no longer exists or is no longer relevant.
1526.example: I told him that if he doesn't get his act together, he's history.
He has had a lot of history with the police.

1527.definition: A blow; a punch; a striking against; the collision of one body against another; the stroke that touches anything.
The complete play, when the batter reaches base without the benefit of a walk, error, or fielder’s choice.
1527.example: The catcher got a hit to lead off the fifth.

1527.definition: A dose of an illegal or addictive drug.
1527.example: Where am I going to get my next hit?

1527.definition: A peculiarly apt expression or turn of thought; a phrase which hits the mark.

1528.definition: To manage to touch (a target) in the right place.

1528.example: Somebody's been here! Hit the lights!
We hit the grocery store on the way to the park.

1528.definition: To encounter an obstacle or other difficulty.
1528.example: You'll hit some nasty thunderstorms if you descend too late.  We hit a lot of traffic coming back from the movies.
The economy was hit by a recession.  The hurricane hit his fishing business hard.
The external web servers hit DBSRV7, but the internal web server hits DBSRV3.

1529.example: Keep a firm hold on the handlebars.

1529.definition: An act or instance of holding.
1529.example: Can I have a hold of the baby?

1529.definition: An order that something is to be reserved or delayed, limiting or preventing how it can be dealt with.
1529.example: Senator X placed a hold on the bill, then went to the library and placed a hold on a book.
We have a hold here for you.

1529.definition: A position or grip used to control the opponent.
1529.example: He got him in a tight hold and pinned him to the mat.

1529.definition: The percentage the house wins on a gamble, the house or bookmaker's hold.
1529.example: The House Hold on the game is 10,000, this is the amount of decision or risk the house wishes to assume.

1529.definition: The wager amount, the total hold.
1529.example: As of Monday night the total Melbourne Cup hold was $848,015

1529.definition: The cargo area of a ship or aircraft (often holds or cargo hold).

1530.definition: To organise an event or meeting (usually in passive voice).
1530.example: Elections will be held on the first Sunday of next month.

1530.definition: In a food or drink order at an informal restaurant etc., requesting that a component normally included in that order be omitted.
1530.example: A martini, please, and hold the olive.

1531.example: Put your umbrella in the umbrella holder.

1531.definition: A person who temporarily or permanently possesses something.
1531.example: He's been an account holder with us since 2004.

1533.definition: A hollow place or cavity; an excavation; a pit; an opening in or through a solid body, a fabric, etc.; a perforation; a rent; a fissure.
1533.example: There’s a hole in my shoe.  Her stocking has a hole in it.

1533.definition: A weakness; a flaw or ambiguity.
1533.example: I have found a hole in your argument.

1533.definition: An orifice, in particular the anus. When used with shut it always refers to the mouth.
(particularly in the phrase "get one's hole") Sex, or a sex partner.
1533.example: Are you going out to get your hole tonight?

1533.definition: An undesirable place to live or visit; a hovel.

1533.example: If you find yourself in a hole, stop digging.

1534.definition: A day on which a festival, religious event, or national celebration is traditionally observed.
A period during which pupils do not attend their school; often plural; rarely used for students at university (usually: vacation).
1534.example: I want to take a French course this summer holiday.

1534.definition: A period during which, by agreement, the usual payments are not made.

1535.definition: Dedicated to a religious purpose or a god.
1535.example: I'm planning to visit the holy city of Jerusalem this Christmas.

1535.definition: Morally perfect or flawless, or nearly so.
1535.example: My grandmother is a very holy woman.

1535.definition: Used as an intensifier in various interjections.
1535.example: Holy cow, I can’t believe he actually lost the race!

1536.definition: At or in one's place of residence or one's customary or official location; at home
1536.example: Everyone's gone to watch the game; there's nobody home.

1536.definition: Into the right, proper or stowed position

1537.definition: The locality where a thing is usually found, or was first found, or where it is naturally abundant; habitat; seat.

1538.definition: Work that is done at home, especially school exercises assigned by a teacher.
1538.example: You must do your homework before you can watch television.

1538.definition: Preliminary or preparatory work, such as research.
1538.example: The speaker had certainly done his homework before delivering the lecture.

1539.definition: (of a person or institution) Scrupulous with regard to telling the truth; not given to swindling, lying, or fraud; upright.
1539.example: We’re the most honest people you will ever come across.

1539.definition: (of a statement) True, especially as far as is known by the person making the statement; fair; unbiased.
Earned or acquired in a fair manner.

1540.example: Honestly, I didn't believe a word she said.

1541.definition: A woman, especially an attractive one.
1541.example: Man, there are some fine honeys here tonight!

1542.definition: Recognition of importance or value; respect; veneration (of someone, usually for being morally upright or successful)
1542.example: The crowds gave the returning general much honor and praise.

1542.definition: The state of being morally upright, honest, noble, virtuous, and magnanimous; excellence of character; the perception of such a state; favourable reputation; dignity
1542.example: He was a most perfect knight, for he had great honor and chivalry.

1542.definition: A token of praise or respect; something that represents praiseworthiness or respect, such as a prize or award given by the state to a citizen
1542.example: Audie Murphy received many honors, such as the Distinguished Service Cross.
I had the honour of dining with the ambassador.

1542.definition: (in the plural) the privilege of going first
1542.example: I'll let you have the honours, Bob—go ahead.

1542.definition: A cause of respect and fame; a glory; an excellency; an ornament.
1542.example: He is an honour to his nation.

1542.definition: (in the plural) (courses for) an honours degree: a university qualification of the highest rank
1542.example: At university I took honours in modern history.

1543.definition: Removal or expulsion from a group or activity
1543.example: He is not handling this job, so we're giving him the hook.

1543.definition: A catchy musical phrase which forms the basis of a popular song.
Part of a system's operation that can be intercepted to change or augment its behaviour.
1543.example: We've added hooks to allow undefined message types to be handled with custom code.

1544.example: Hook the bag here, and the conveyor will carry it away.

1544.definition: To catch with a hook (hook a fish).
1544.example: He hooked a snake accidentally, and was so scared he dropped his rod into the water.

1544.definition: To insert in a curved way reminiscent of a hook.
1544.example: He hooked his fingers through his belt loops.

1544.definition: To ensnare or obligate someone, as if with a hook.
1544.example: A free trial is a good way to hook customers.
If you hook your network cable into the jack, you'll be on the network.

1544.definition: (usually in passive) To make addicted; to captivate.
1544.example: He had gotten hooked on cigarettes in his youth.

1544.definition: To engage in the illegal maneuver of hooking (i.e., using the hockey stick to trip or block another player)
1544.example: The opposing team's forward hooked me, but the referee didn't see it, so no penalty.
I had a cheap flat in the bad part of town, and I could watch the working girls hooking from my bedroom window.

1545.definition: The feeling of trust, confidence, belief or expectation that something wished for can or will happen.
1545.example: After losing my job, there's no hope of being able to afford my world cruise.

1545.definition: A person or thing that is a source of hope.
1545.example: We still have one hope left: my roommate might see the note I left on the table.

1546.definition: To want something to happen, with a sense of expectation that it might.
1546.example: I am still hoping that all will turn out well.
I hope you all the best.

1547.definition: It is hoped that; I hope; we hope.
1547.example: Hopefully, my father will arrive in time for the show.

1548.definition: Giving no ground of hope; promising nothing desirable; desperate.

1548.example: He's a hopeless writer, but can draw very well.

1550.definition: Something horrible; that which excites horror.
1550.example: I saw many horrors during the war.

1550.definition: A nasty or ill-behaved person; a rascal or terror.
1550.example: The neighbour's kids are a pack of little horrors!

1553.definition: One which receives or entertains a guest, socially, commercially, or officially.
1553.example: A good host is always considerate of the guest’s needs.

1553.definition: A person or organization responsible for running an event.
1553.example: Our company is host of the annual conference this year.

1553.definition: A moderator or master of ceremonies for a performance.
1553.example: The host was terrible, but the acts themselves were good.

1553.definition: A cell or organism which harbors another organism or biological entity, usually a parasite.
1553.example: Viruses depend on the host that they infect in order to be able to reproduce.

1553.definition: (evolution) An organism bearing certain genetic material.
1553.example: The so-called junk DNA is known, so far, to provide no apparent benefit to its host.

1553.definition: A large number of items; a large inventory.
1553.example: The dealer stocks a host of parts for my Model A.

1554.definition: (of an object) Having a high temperature.

Caring and friendly, of relations to another person.
Communicating a sense of comfort, ease, or pleasantness

3505.example: a warm debate, with strong words exchanged

3506.definition: To caution or admonish (someone) against unwise or unacceptable behaviour.
3506.example: Don't let me catch you running in the corridor again, I warn you.

3506.definition: (chiefly with "off", "away", and similar words) To advise or order to go or stay away.
3506.example: A sign warns trespassers off/away from the site.

3507.definition: Something spoken or written that is intended to warn.
3507.example: The boss gave him a warning that he would be fired if he did not desist from his behaviour.

3508.example: Dishwashers wash dishes much more efficiently than most humans.

3508.definition: To move or erode by the force of water in motion.
3508.example: Heavy rains wash a road or an embankment.
I wash every morning after getting up.

3508.definition: To cover with water or any liquid; to wet; to fall on and moisten.
To move with a lapping or swashing sound; to lap or splash.
To bear without injury the operation of being washed.
To overlay with a thin coat of metal.

3509.definition: Clothing, bedlinen or soft furnishings that have been, are currently being, or are to be washed; laundry.
3509.example: My mother used to do the washing on a Monday

3509.definition: (often in the plural) The residue after an ore, etc, has been washed
3509.example: The washings have a higher concentration of metal

3509.definition: A place where a precious metal found in gravel is separated from lighter material by washing.

3511.example: The cage was littered with animal waste

3511.definition: The action or progress of wasting; extravagant consumption or ineffectual use.

3512.definition: To squander (money or resources) uselessly; to spend (time) idly.
3512.example: We wasted millions of dollars and several years on that project.

3513.example: More people today carry a watch on their wrists than in their pockets.

3513.definition: A particular time period when guarding is kept.
3513.example: The second watch of the night began at midnight.

3513.definition: A person or group of people who guard.
3513.example: The watch stopped the travelers at the city gates.

3514.definition: To look at, see, or view for a period of time.
To observe over a period of time; to notice or pay attention.
3514.example: Put a little baking soda in some vinegar and watch what happens.
He has to watch the kids that afternoon.

3514.definition: To be wary or cautious of.
3514.example: You should watch that guy. He has a reputation for lying.

3514.definition: To attend to dangers to or regarding.
To be vigilant or on one's guard.
3514.example: For some must watch, while some must sleep: So runs the world away.

3515.definition: A substance (of molecular formula H₂O) found at room temperature and pressure as a clear liquid; it is present naturally as rain, and found in rivers, lakes and seas; its solid form is ice and its gaseous form is steam.
3515.example: By the action of electricity, the water was resolved into its two parts, oxygen and hydrogen.

3515.definition: The aforementioned liquid, considered one of the Classical elements or basic elements of alchemy.
3515.example: And God said, Let the waters under the heaven be gathered together unto one place, and let the dry land appear: and it was so.

3515.definition: Water in a body; an area of open water.
3515.example: The boat was found within the territorial waters.

3515.definition: (in the plural or in the singular) A state of affairs; conditions; usually with an adjective indicating an adverse condition.
3515.example: The rough waters of change will bring about the calm after the storm.
I know he'll succeed. I feel it in my waters.

3515.definition: The limpidity and lustre of a precious stone, especially a diamond.
3515.example: a diamond of the first water is perfectly pure and transparent

3516.definition: A moving disturbance in the level of a body of liquid; an undulation.
3516.example: The wave traveled from the center of the lake before breaking on the shore.

3516.definition: A shape that alternatingly curves in opposite directions.
3516.example: Her hair had a nice wave to it.

3516.definition: A loose back-and-forth movement, as of the hands.
3516.example: He dismissed her with a wave of the hand.

3516.definition: A sudden unusually large amount of something that is temporarily experienced.
3516.example: A wave of emotion overcame her when she thought about her son who was killed in battle.

3517.definition: To move back and forth repeatedly and somewhat loosely.
3517.example: The flag waved in the gentle breeze.

3517.definition: (metonymic) To call attention to, or give a direction or command to, by a waving motion, as of the hand; to signify by waving; to beckon; to signal; to indicate.
3517.example: I waved goodbye from across the room.

3517.definition: To swing and miss at a pitch.
To cause to move back and forth repeatedly.
3517.example: The starter waved the flag to begin the race.

3517.definition: To relinquish (a right etc.); to give up claim to; to forego.
3517.example: If you waive the right to be silent, anything you say can be used against you in a court of law.

3518.example: I'm a way better singer than Emma.
I used to live way over there.

3519.definition: A method or manner of doing something; a mannerism.
3519.example: You're going about it the wrong way.  He's known for his quirky ways.  I don't like the way she looks at me.
When I returned home, I found my house and belongings in a most terrible way.

3519.definition: A tradition within the modern pagan faith of Heathenry, dedication to a specific deity or craft, Way of wyrd, Way of runes, Way of Thor etc.
3519.example: To walk the Way of the Runes, you must experience the runes as they manifest both in the part of Midgard that lies outside yourself and the worlds within. (Diana Paxson)

3519.definition: A degree, an amount, a sense.
3519.example: In a large way, crocodiles and alligators are similar.

3519.definition: (As the head of an interjectory clause, followed by an infinitive starting with “to”) Acknowledges that a task has been done well, chiefly in expressions of sarcastic congratulation.
3519.example: Way to ruin the moment, guys.

3520.definition: (personal) The plural form of you, including everyone being addressed.
(personal, often considered patronising) A second- or third-person pronoun for a person in the speaker's care.
3520.example: How are we feeling this morning?

3521.definition: Lacking in force (usually strength) or ability.
3521.example: The child was too weak to move the boulder.

3521.definition: Unable to sustain a great weight, pressure, or strain.
3521.example: a weak timber; a weak rope

3521.definition: Unable to withstand temptation, urgency, persuasion, etc.; easily impressed, moved, or overcome; accessible; vulnerable.
Dilute, lacking in taste or potency.
3521.example: We were served stale bread and weak tea.

3521.definition: That does not ionize completely into anions and cations in a solution.
3521.example: a weak acid;  a weak base

3521.definition: Not having power to convince; not supported by force of reason or truth; unsustained.
3521.example: The prosecution advanced a weak case.
a weak sentence; a weak style
a weak market; wheat is weak at present

3522.example: In a small number of horses, muscle weakness may progress to paralysis.
His inability to speak in front of an audience was his weakness.
She is an athlete who has a weakness for chocolate.

3523.definition: A great amount; an abundance or plenty.
3523.example: She brings a wealth of knowledge to the project.

3524.definition: An instrument of attack or defense in combat or hunting, e.g. most guns, missiles, or swords.
3524.example: The club that is now mostly used for golf was once a common weapon.

3524.definition: An instrument or other means of harming or exerting control over another.
3524.example: Money is the main weapon of modern oligarchs.

3525.definition: To carry or have equipped on or about one's body, as an item of clothing, equipment, decoration, etc.
3525.example: He's wearing some nice pants today.  She wore her medals with pride.  Please wear your seatbelt.  Can you wear makeup and sunscreen at the same time?  He was wearing his lunch after tripping and falling into the buffet.

3525.definition: To have or carry on one's person habitually, consistently; or, to maintain in a particular fashion or manner.
3525.example: He wears eyeglasses.  She wears her hair in braids.

3525.definition: To bear or display in one's aspect or appearance.
3525.example: She wore a smile all day.  He walked out of the courtroom wearing an air of satisfaction.

3525.definition: (with "it") To overcome one's reluctance and endure a (previously specified) situation.
3525.example: I know you don't like working with him, but you'll just have to wear it.

3525.definition: To eat away at, erode, diminish, or consume gradually; to cause a gradual deterioration in; to produce (some change) through attrition, exposure, or constant use.
3525.example: You're going to wear a hole in the bottom of those shoes.  The water has slowly worn a channel into these rocks.  Long illness had worn the bloom from her cheeks.  Exile had worn the man to a shadow.

3525.definition: To undergo gradual deterioration; become impaired; be reduced or consumed gradually due to any continued process, activity, or use.
3525.example: The tiles were wearing thin due to years of children's feet.

3525.definition: To exhaust, fatigue, expend, or weary.
3525.example: His neverending criticism has finally worn my patience.  Toil and care soon wear the spirit.  Our physical advantage allowed us to wear the other team out and win.

3525.definition: To last or remain durable under hard use or over time; to retain usefulness, value, or desirable qualities under any continued strain or long period of time; sometimes said of a person, regarding the quality of being easy or difficult to tolerate.
3525.example: Don't worry, this fabric will wear. These pants will last you for years.  This color wears so well. I must have washed this sweater a thousand times.  I have to say, our friendship has worn pretty well.  It's hard to get to know him, but he wears well.

3525.definition: (in the phrase "wearing on (someone)") To cause annoyance, irritation, fatigue, or weariness near the point of an exhaustion of patience.
3525.example: Her high pitched voice is really wearing on me lately.

3525.definition: (of time) To pass slowly, gradually or tediously.
3525.example: wear on, wear away.  As the years wore on, we seemed to have less and less in common.

3525.definition: To ward off; prevent from approaching or entering; drive off; repel.
3525.example: to wear the wolf from the sheep

3526.definition: Unpleasant or destructive atmospheric conditions, and their effects.
3526.example: Wooden garden furniture must be well oiled as it is continuously exposed to weather.

3527.definition: The silken structure which a spider builds using silk secreted from the spinnerets at the caudal tip of its abdomen; a spiderweb.
3527.example: The sunlight glistened in the dew on the web.

3527.definition: (sometimes capitalized) Specifically, the World Wide Web.
3527.example: Let me search the web for that.

3527.definition: The part of a baseball mitt between the forefinger and thumb, the webbing.
3527.example: He caught the ball in the web.
The gazebo's roof was a web made of thin strips of wood.

3527.definition: (usually with "spin", "weave", or similar verbs) A tall tale with more complexity than a myth or legend.
3527.example: Careful—she knows how to spin a good web, but don't lean too hard on what she says.

3529.definition: Marriage ceremony; ritual officially celebrating the beginning of a marriage.
3529.example: Her announcement was quite a surprise, coming a month after she published the words "I hate weddings with a passion and a fury I can only partially explain rationally."

3529.definition: Joining of two or more parts.
3529.example: The wedding of our three companies took place last week.

3530.definition: A subdivision of the month into longer periods of work days punctuated by shorter weekend periods of days for markets, rest, or religious observation such as a sabbath.
3530.example: A 4-day week consists of Monday, Tuesday, Wednesday, and Thursday.

3530.definition: Seven days after (sometimes before) a specified date.

3532.definition: Happening once a week, or every week.
3532.example: He's going for his weekly check-up at the hospital.

3533.definition: Often with "out", to measure a certain amount of something by its weight, e.g. for sale.
3533.example: He weighed out two kilos of oranges for a client.

3533.definition: To determine the intrinsic value or merit of an object, to evaluate.
3533.example: You have been weighed in the balance and found wanting.
I weigh ten and a half stone.

3534.definition: An object, such as a weight plate or barbell, used for strength training.

3534.example: the weight of care or business

3535.definition: Having an unusually strange character or behaviour.
3535.example: There are lots of weird people in this place.
It was quite weird to bump into all my ex-girlfriends on the same day.
There was a weird light shining above the hill.

3536.definition: Whose arrival is a cause of joy; received with gladness; admitted willingly to the house, entertainment, or company.
Free to have or enjoy gratuitously.
3536.example: You are welcome to the use of my library.

3537.definition: To accept something willingly or gladly.

3539.example: I had been sick, but now I'm well.

3541.definition: Used to acknowledge a statement or situation.
3541.example: “I didn't like the music.” “Well, I thought it was good.”

3541.definition: An exclamation of surprise (often doubled or tripled).
3541.example: Well, well, well, what do we have here?
Well! There was no need to say that in front of my mother!

3541.definition: Used in speech to express the overcoming of reluctance to say something.
3541.example: It was a bit... well... too loud.

3541.definition: Used in speech to fill gaps, particularly at the beginning of a response to a question; filled pause.
3541.example: “So what have you been doing?” “Well, we went for a picnic, and then it started raining so we came home early.”

3543.definition: Of, facing, situated in, or related to the west.

3544.definition: Made up of liquid or moisture, usually (but not always) water.
Of an object, etc.: covered or impregnated with liquid, usually (but not always) water.
3544.example: I went out in the rain and now my clothes are all wet.

3544.definition: Of calligraphy and fountain pens: depositing a large amount of ink from the nib or the feed.
3544.example: This pen’s a wet writer, so it’ll feather on this cheap paper.

3544.definition: Of weather or a time period: rainy.
3544.example: It’s going to be wet tomorrow.

3544.definition: Of a person: inexperienced in a profession or task; having the characteristics of a rookie.
3544.example: That guy’s wet; after all, he just started yesterday.

3544.definition: (of women) Sexually aroused and thus having the vulva moistened with vaginal secretions.
Ineffectual, feeble, showing no strength of character.
Employing, or done by means of, water or some other liquid.
3544.example: the wet extraction of copper, in distinction from dry extraction in which dry heat or fusion is employed
a wet affair; a wet job; wet stuff

3545.definition: That which; those that; the thing that.

3545.example: I will do what I can to help you.

3546.example: Whatever he does, he will still lose the game.

3546.definition: (relative) Anything; sometimes used to indicate that the speaker does not care about options.

3548.definition: A recurring or cyclical course of events.

3549.definition: (interrogative) At what time? At which time? Upon which occasion or circumstance? Used to introduce direct or indirect questions about time.
3549.example: Do you know when they arrived?

3549.definition: At an earlier time and under different, usually less favorable, circumstances.
3549.example: He's mister high and mighty now, but I remember him when.

3549.definition: (relative) At which, on which, during which: often omitted or replaced with that.
3549.example: That was the day when the Twin Towers fell.

3550.definition: At (or as soon as) that time that; at the (or any and every) time that; if.
3550.example: A player wins when [as soon as, or at any time that, if] she has four cards of the same suit.

3550.definition: During the time that; at the time of the action of the following clause or participle phrase.
3550.example: Be careful when crossing the street.

3550.definition: At what time; at which time.
3550.example: I am here till Friday, when [i.e. at which time] I leave for Senegal.

3550.definition: Since; given the fact that; considering that.
3550.example: I don't see the point of putting up Christmas decorations when I am the only person who is going to see them.

3550.definition: Whereas; although; at the same time as; in spite of the fact that.

3551.definition: The time at which something happens.

I recall when they were called the Greys.

3552.definition: (interrogative) When ever: emphatic form of when.
3552.example: Whenever will I find time to finish that jigsaw?

3553.definition: At the (single) time that, no matter when.
