3554.definition: Interrogative adverb, used in either a direct or indirect question: at what place; to what place; what place.
3554.example: He asked where I grew up.
Where would we be without our parents?
That is the place where we first met.

3555.definition: While on the contrary; although; whereas.
3555.example: Where Susy has trouble coloring inside the lines, Johnny has already mastered shading.

3555.definition: At or in which place or situation.
3555.example: He is looking for a house where he can have a complete office.
The snowbirds travel where it is warm.
Their job is to go where they are called.

3555.definition: In a position, case, etc., in which.
3555.example: Where no provision under this Act is applicable, the case shall be decided in accordance with the customary practices.

3556.definition: The place in which something happens.
3556.example: A good article will cover the who, the what, the when, the where, the why and the how.
He lives within five miles of where he was born.

3557.definition: In contrast; whilst on the contrary; although.
3557.example: He came first in the race, whereas his brother came last.

3558.example: Wherever have you been all my life?

3559.definition: Used to introduce an indirect interrogative question that consists of multiple alternative possibilities (usually with correlative or).
3559.example: He chose the correct answer, but I don't know whether it was by luck or (whether it was) by skill.

3559.definition: Without a correlative, used to introduce a simple indirect question.
3559.example: Do you know whether he's coming?

3559.definition: Used to introduce a disjunctive adverbial clause which qualifies the main clause of the sentence (with correlative or).
3559.example: He's coming, whether you like it or not.

3560.definition: (interrogative) What one or ones (of those mentioned or implied).
3560.example: By now, you must surely know which is which.

3560.definition: (relative) Introduces a relative clause giving further information about something previously mentioned.
3560.example: He had to leave, which was very difficult.

3561.example: He was sleeping while I was singing.
This case, while interesting, is a bit frustrating.
I'll wait while you've finished painting.
While you're at school you may live at home.

3561.definition: (public policy) Used to denote an individual experiencing racial profiling when performing a seemingly benign activity.
3561.example: He was detained for four hours at the store yesterday. His crime? Shopping while black.

3562.definition: An uncertain duration of time, a period of time.
3562.example: He lectured for quite a long while.

3565.definition: Bright and colourless; reflecting equal quantities of all frequencies of visible light.
3565.example: Write in black ink on white paper.

3565.definition: Relatively light or pale in colour.

3565.example: The white pieces in this set are in fact made of light green glass.

3565.definition: Characterised by the presence of snow.

3567.definition: (interrogative) What person or people; which person or people; asks for the identity of someone. (used in a direct or indirect question)
3567.example: I don't know who it is. (indirect question)

3567.definition: (interrogative) What is one's position; asks whether someone deserves to say or do something.
3567.example: I don't like what you did, but who am I to criticize you? I've done worse.
It was a nice man who helped us.

3568.definition: (interrogative) Who ever: an emphatic form of who.
3568.example: Whoever thought up that stupid idea?

3568.definition: (fused relative) Any person or persons that.
3568.example: Whoever breaks the law will be punished.

3568.definition: (fused relative) The person that (no matter who).
3568.example: I don't know what it is. Ask whoever put it there.

3568.definition: Regardless of the person or persons that.
3568.example: Whoever stole the painting, the police will catch the thief in no time.
I don't care who gets it; give it to whoever.

3568.definition: Misspelling of who ever other than in interrogative use.
3568.example: *He is the tallest man whoever lived. (incorrect usage)

3569.example: He is of whole mind, but the same cannot be said about his physical state.

3569.definition: (of food) From which none of its constituents has been removed.

3570.definition: Something complete, without any parts missing.
3570.example: This variety of fascinating details didn't fall together into an enjoyable, coherent whole.

3571.definition: (relative) Used to refer to a previously mentioned person or people.
3571.example: He's a person with whom I work. (defining)

3571.definition: (fused relative, archaic outside set patterns) The person(s) whom; whomever.
3571.example: To whom it may concern, all business of John Smith Ltd. has now been transferred to Floggitt & Runne.

3572.definition: (interrogative) That or those of whom or belonging to whom.
3572.example: Several people have lost their suitcases. Whose have you found?

3572.definition: (relative) That or those of whom or belonging to whom.
3572.example: This car is blocking the way, but Mr Smith, whose it is, will be here shortly.

3573.definition: For which cause, reason, or purpose (relative adverb).
3573.example: That's the reason why I did that.

3575.example: That was a wicked guitar solo, bro!

3576.definition: Having a large physical extent from side to side.
3576.example: We walked down a wide corridor.
The inquiry had a wide remit.

3576.definition: Operating at the side of the playing area.
3576.example: That team needs a decent wide player.

3576.definition: On one side or the other of the mark; too far sideways from the mark, the wicket, the batsman, etc.
3576.example: Too bad! That was a great passing-shot, but it's wide.

3576.definition: (now rare) Vast, great in extent, extensive.
Of or supporting a greater range of text characters than can fit into the traditional 8-bit representation.
3576.example: a wide character; a wide stream

3577.example: A few shots were fired but they all went wide.

3580.definition: The female of a pair of mated animals.
3580.example: A new wife for the gander is introduced into the pen.

3581.definition: Untamed; not domesticated; specifically, in an unbroken line of undomesticated animals (as opposed to feral, referring to undomesticated animals whose ancestors were domesticated).
3581.example: Przewalski's horses are the only remaining wild horses.

3581.definition: From or relating to wild creatures.

3581.example: I was filled with wild rage when I discovered the infidelity, and punched a hole in the wall.
The fraternity was infamous for its wild parties, which frequently resulted in police involvement.
Her mother was wild with fear when she didn't return home after the party.
After a week on the trail without a mirror, my hair was wild and dirty.
I'm not wild about the idea of a two day car trip with my nephews, but it's my only option.
The novice archer fired a wild shot and hit her opponent's target.

3581.definition: Exposed to the wind and sea; unsheltered.

3581.example: Did you hear? Pat won the lottery! - Wow, that's wild!

3581.definition: Able to stand in for others, e.g. a card in games, or a text character in computer pattern matching.
3581.example: In this card game, aces are wild: they can take the place of any other card.

3583.definition: One's independent faculty of choice; the ability to be able to exercise one's choice or intention.
3583.example: Of course, man's will is often regulated by his reason.

3583.definition: One's intention or decision; someone's orders or commands.
3583.example: Eventually I submitted to my parents' will.

3583.definition: The act of choosing to do something; a person’s conscious intent or volition.
3583.example: Most creatures have a will to live.

3583.definition: Desire, longing. (Now generally merged with later senses.)
3583.example: He felt a great will to make a pilgrimage to the Holy Land.

3584.definition: Ready to do something that is not (can't be expected as) a matter of course.
3584.example: If my boyfriend isn't willing to change his drinking habits, I will split up with him.

3585.example: Our first win of the season put us in high spirits.

3586.definition: To gain (a prize) by succeeding in competition or contest.
3586.example: to win the jackpot in a lottery;  to win a bottle of wine in a raffle
Who would win in a fight between an octopus and a dolphin?

3586.definition: To have power, coercion or control.
3586.example: Ever since the 2013 Boston Marathon bombing, Bostonians now run as "One Boston." The terrorists did not win.
The company hopes to win an order from the government worth over 5 million dollars.

3586.definition: To cause a victory for someone.
3586.example: The policy success should win the elections for Mr. Smith.

3587.definition: Real or perceived movement of atmospheric air usually caused by convection or differences in air pressure.
3587.example: As they accelerated onto the motorway, the wind tore the plywood off the car's roof-rack.

3587.definition: Air artificially put in motion by any force or action.
3587.example: the wind of a cannon ball;  the wind of a bellows
After the second lap he was already out of wind.

3587.definition: News of an event, especially by hearsay or gossip. (Used with catch, often in the past tense.)
3587.example: Steve caught wind of Martha's dalliance with his best friend.

3588.definition: To cause (someone) to become breathless, as by a blow to the abdomen, or by physical exertion, running, etc.
3588.example: The boxer was winded during round two.

3588.definition: To perceive or follow by scent.
To turn coils of (a cord or something similar) around something.
3588.example: to wind thread on a spool or into a ball

3588.definition: To tighten the spring of a clockwork mechanism such as that of a clock.
3588.example: Please wind that old-fashioned alarm clock.

3588.definition: To travel in a way that is not straight.
3588.example: Vines wind round a pole.  The river winds through the plain.

3588.definition: To cover or surround with something coiled about.
3588.example: to wind a rope with twine

3589.definition: The inedible parts of a grain-producing plant.
3589.example: To separate out the chaff, early cultures tossed baskets of grain into the air and let the wind blow away the lighter chaff.

3589.definition: A period of time when something is available.
3589.example: launch window;  window of opportunity;  You have a two-hour window of clear weather to finish working on the lawn.

3590.example: It was a long and windy night.

3590.definition: Unsheltered and open to the wind.
3590.example: They made love in a windy bus shelter.
They made windy promises they would not keep.

3591.definition: An alcoholic beverage made by fermenting the juice of grapes.
3591.example: She ordered some wine for the meal.
I'd like three beers and two wines, please.

3592.definition: A part of something that is lesser in size than the main body, such as an extension from the main building.
3592.example: the west wing of the hospital

3592.definition: On the Enneagram, one of the two adjacent types to an enneatype that forms an individual's subtype of his or her enneatype
3592.example: Tom's a 4 on the Enneagram, with a 3 wing.

3595.definition: To move an object over, maintaining contact, with the intention of removing some substance from the surface. (Compare rub.)
3595.example: I wiped the sweat from my brow with the back of my hand.
I accidentally wiped my hard drive.

3595.definition: To remove an expression from one's face.
3595.example: You should wipe that smirk off your face before the boss comes in.

3595.definition: To have all members of a party die in a single campaign, event, or battle; to be wiped out.
3595.example: If you try to fight that boss underprepared, you're definitely gonna wipe.

3596.example: This election is going to go right to the wire

3596.definition: (usually in the plural) Any of the system of wires used to operate the puppets in a puppet show; hence, the network of hidden influences controlling the action of a person or organization; strings.
